			<a name="usage"/>
            <subsection name="Usage">
                <ol type="1">
                    <li>Unzip
                        <tt>mydoggy-1.1.0.zip</tt>
                        to the directory you wish to unzip MyDoggy 1.1.0.
                    </li>
                    <li>Move to
                        <tt>lib</tt>
                        directory where you can found mydoggy jar files.
                    </li>
                    <li>To use mydoggy add to your classpath
                        <tt>mydoggy_1.1.0-api.jar</tt> and
                        <tt>mydoggy_1.1.0-plaf.jar</tt>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                <h4>Transparency on Windows 2000/XP</h4>
                <p>
                    To see in action the transparency effect you have to put TransparencyManager.dll into a system
                    directory. Refers to java property "java.library.path" for those directories.
                    <br/>
                    You can found the precompiled TransparencyManager.dll file into <tt>/lib/win32</tt>
                    starting from the directory you have choosed to unzip mydoggy.
                </p>
            </subsection>

			<a name="mydoggyset"/>
            <subsection name="MyDoggySet Usage">
                <h4>Windows 2000/XP</h4>
                <ol type="1">
                    <li>Unzip
                        <tt>mydoggy-1.1.0.zip</tt>
                        to the directory you wish to unzip MyDoggy 1.1.0. These instructions assume you chose
                        <tt>C:\Program Files\mydoggy-1.1.0</tt>
                    </li>
                    <li>Move to
                        <tt>bin</tt>
                        directory.
                        <tt>&quot;C:\Program Files\mydoggy-1.1.0\bin&quot;</tt>
                    </li>
                    <li>In the same dialog, make sure that
                        <tt>JAVA_HOME</tt>
                        is set to the location of your JDK, eg.
                        <tt>C:\Program Files\Java\jdk1.5.0_02</tt>
                    </li>
                    <li>Run
                        <tt>mydoggyset</tt>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                <h4>Unix-based Operating Systems (Linux, Solaris and Mac OS X)</h4>
                <ol type="1">
                    <li>Unzip
                        <tt>mydoggy-1.1.0.zip</tt>
                        to the directory you wish to install MyDoggy 1.1.0. These instructions assume you chose
                        <tt>/usr/local/mydoggy-1.1.0</tt>
                    </li>
                    <li>Move to
                        <tt>bin</tt>
                        directory.
                        <tt>&quot;/usr/local/mydoggy-1.1.0/bin&quot;</tt>
                    </li>
                    <li>In the same dialog, make sure that
                        <tt>JAVA_HOME</tt>
                        is set to the location of your JDK, eg.
                        <tt>/usr/java/jdk1.5.0_02</tt>
                    </li>
                    <li>Run
                        <tt>./mydoggyset.sh</tt>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </subsection>

